458
00:29:18,139 --> 00:29:20,681
but it also means you don't have to process all that stuff.

459
00:29:20,721 --> 00:29:22,603
You're just graying it out and that gives you

460
00:29:22,623 --> 00:29:25,586
a lot more cycles to work on the area

461
00:29:25,626 --> 00:29:27,288
that you're showing in the center of the screen,

462
00:29:27,308 --> 00:29:28,309
which can be very handy.

463
00:29:28,629 --> 00:29:30,311
You can keep up a very high frame rate

464
00:29:30,371 --> 00:29:31,553
in the areas that you do show.

465
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:36,122
This is likely to be coming to mobile in the future.

466
00:29:36,703 --> 00:29:39,785
And where eye tracking, as I said, is really interesting.

467
00:29:39,865 --> 00:29:43,188
Right now, the foveal view is done by sort of brute forcing,

468
00:29:43,248 --> 00:29:46,130
saying the only thing to look at is this one thing right in front of you.

469
00:29:46,731 --> 00:29:50,774
But wouldn't it be great if we could get to the point where wherever you happen to look,

470
00:29:50,834 --> 00:29:55,738
that's the only area we render in high resolution, and the rest of it we don't have to bother.

471
00:29:56,119 --> 00:29:59,561
And, in fact, with eye tracking rigs that are out there, there will probably be demos.

472
00:29:59,982 --> 00:30:01,903
I haven't had a chance to see what's being demoed here.

