00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:03,824
But the trick is there's a whole lot that you have to get right.

506
00:32:03,905 --> 00:32:08,650
There are entire talks given to even just single elements of this, certainly this whole

507
00:32:08,710 --> 00:32:09,491
range of things.

508
00:32:09,912 --> 00:32:11,514
I've listed some of the more common.

509
00:32:11,954 --> 00:32:15,136
areas that you need to get right. I've talked about getting the frame rate and the head

510
00:32:15,176 --> 00:32:19,278
tracking right, but that's only the beginning of the puzzle. There are so many other things

511
00:32:19,318 --> 00:32:24,181
that you need to do to try and recreate what we see with our eyes that it frankly at this

512
00:32:24,281 --> 00:32:28,544
point with the processors, with the screens and everything we have, it is impossible to

513
00:32:28,604 --> 00:32:33,486
get really close to what our eyes and brains are capable of seeing. Happily though it feels

514
00:32:33,526 --> 00:32:37,889
that we've gotten just good enough in the last few years that it starts to be a convincing

515
00:32:39,694 --> 00:32:43,855
simulation of that. One of the things that isn't even on this list that I've seen some

516
00:32:43,875 --> 00:32:49,378
interesting first steps on is the fact that your eye works a bit like a camera and that

517
00:32:49,418 --> 00:32:53,100
you focus with muscles in your eye changing the shape of your eye and

518
00:32:54,841 --> 00:32:59,904
of the lens in your eye to focus, as a camera does, close and far away.

519
00:32:59,944 --> 00:33:03,205
So if you hold your finger close to your eye, you focus on it,

520
00:33:03,245 --> 00:33:05,027
and everything else in the background is blurred.

521
00:33:05,087 --> 00:33:08,168
And likewise, if you look in the distance, you can hold your finger up,

522
00:33:08,228 --> 00:33:09,129
and that's kind of blurry.

523
00:33:09,189 --> 00:33:13,311
It's because the lens in your eye is actually stretching and changing shape.

524
00:33:14,292 --> 00:33:25,077
In current systems that are out there now, they can't account for that, but there will be systems coming in the fairly near future that will be able to actually, even with one eye closed, be able to give you a sense of depth.

525
00:33:25,477 --> 00:33:35,202
But right now, one of the miscues that we're getting is that things don't actually change depth of field when you're looking at them through a screen.

526
00:33:35,222 --> 00:33:37,323
You're looking at this screen that's right in front of your eyes.

527
00:33:37,904 --> 00:33:40,566
and you can kind of fake it with some cases,

528
00:33:40,646 --> 00:33:43,408
but it actually doesn't quite do a full job there.

529
00:33:43,808 --> 00:33:45,970
So some part of your brain is saying,

530
00:33:46,030 --> 00:33:47,311
there's something not right here,

531
00:33:47,351 --> 00:33:49,953
and if you're one of those unlucky people who raised your hand,

532
00:33:50,013 --> 00:33:51,934
it's probably making you feel a little bit ill.

533
00:33:52,575 --> 00:33:53,896
So there's a lot to get right.

534
00:33:55,918 --> 00:33:58,159
If anybody here worked on this, don't raise your hand.

535
00:33:58,259 --> 00:34:00,641
I'm sorry I brought this up because I found this online.

536
00:34:00,661 --> 00:34:02,822
I thought it was a great example of what not to do.

537
00:34:03,702 --> 00:34:05,884
And I don't want to hit these people too hard because it's

538
00:34:05,904 --> 00:34:09,285
a language teaching program and they really weren't working so

539
00:34:09,325 --> 00:34:10,446
much on VR visuals.

540
00:34:10,886 --> 00:34:13,408
But some of those things I had on that list before are just

541
00:34:13,628 --> 00:34:14,308
broken here.

542
00:34:15,229 --> 00:34:18,611
For example, in the foreground, you've got a kind of blurred

543
00:34:20,312 --> 00:34:26,980
table and a crystal clear sharp bell that just really irritates me because it feels like that, you know,

544
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:33,508
if that, why is that so clear when the rest of it is is blurry and the blurriness is consistent. It should actually be

545
00:34:34,309 --> 00:34:39,175
sharper, closer up, and a little blurrier in the distance or vice versa depending on where the depth of field is.

546
00:34:40,216 --> 00:34:47,523
The worst thing about this, in my opinion though, is that the interface that they have is floating there in space in front of you.

547
00:34:47,803 --> 00:34:50,365
And it turns out that this is a bad thing for a lot of reasons.

548
00:34:50,605 --> 00:34:56,050
For one reason, your eyes are focusing on it and they're converging on this image.

549
00:34:56,531 --> 00:35:00,194
And even though that may be shown left and right in slightly different places,

550
00:35:00,614 --> 00:35:04,678
so that your eyes can say, yes, this is about two feet in front of me.

551
00:35:05,946 --> 00:35:11,189
It is almost certainly being done without any perspective change in the two eyes.

552
00:35:11,249 --> 00:35:14,771
And if it were a real thing, you'd have a different view from your right eye and your

553
00:35:14,811 --> 00:35:17,412
left eye, particularly something that's only a few feet away.

554
00:35:17,693 --> 00:35:20,774
You see a little bit more of the edges of something on the right side with your right

555
00:35:20,874 --> 00:35:21,935
eye, left side, left eye.

556
00:35:22,835 --> 00:35:27,057
And in a lot of shortcuts people use like this for interface, they don't do that.

557
00:35:27,537 --> 00:35:33,679
So it's really a mistake to sort of violate that sense of presence by breaking any of

558
00:35:33,719 --> 00:35:34,239
these rules.

559
00:35:34,799 --> 00:35:39,980
And digetic interface is the term that's been brought up to actually put it into the world.

560
00:35:40,040 --> 00:35:43,741
So in a case like this, you could just as easily put that interface.

561
00:35:44,302 --> 00:35:49,427
on what look like some plaques that are part of the 3D world and that are situated in that

562
00:35:49,707 --> 00:35:56,474
3D world that your eye converges on properly and it makes it a lot easier for someone to

563
00:35:56,554 --> 00:35:56,914
perceive.

564
00:35:57,255 --> 00:36:01,339
It's harder, it's a lot more processing to actually put those up correctly, but this

565
00:36:01,399 --> 00:36:06,284
is one of the things that you, I think, should not take too many shortcuts with or it's really

566
00:36:06,324 --> 00:36:08,226
going to be irritating to the people.

567
00:36:09,109 --> 00:36:11,591
And again, study the way the visual system works.

568
00:36:11,631 --> 00:36:14,034
There's a lot more than I can go into in just this hour.

569
00:36:14,514 --> 00:36:19,659
But another thing, another great lesson that turns out to be true of VR as it was

570
00:36:19,699 --> 00:36:21,260
of other things is that less is more.

571
00:36:21,680 --> 00:36:24,003
You don't actually have to get everything right.

572
00:36:24,403 --> 00:36:28,527
You can actually cut a lot of corners as long as you're very minimal about what you do.

573
00:36:28,567 --> 00:36:30,328
And I'll talk about some examples.

574
00:36:30,849 --> 00:36:33,411
But first I want to remind everybody when you do get it right,

575
00:36:34,172 --> 00:36:35,092
It's pretty amazing.

576
00:36:35,172 --> 00:36:40,875
This is one of the first VR images I saw in the modern VR world that really convinced

577
00:36:43,696 --> 00:36:43,996
me.

578
00:36:45,497 --> 00:36:50,559
I saw one of the early Valve tag rooms before they even announced what the Vive was.

579
00:36:51,640 --> 00:36:55,681
It was just a life-changing experience for me.

580
00:36:55,741 --> 00:36:56,862
In particular, I remember

581
00:36:57,442 --> 00:36:59,864
when I was told, okay, pick up the controller.

582
00:37:00,465 --> 00:37:03,067
And I said, well, I can't see the controller.

583
00:37:03,087 --> 00:37:04,708
So sure you can, look over your shoulder.

584
00:37:04,748 --> 00:37:07,871
And there on a virtual table was a virtual controller.

585
00:37:08,371 --> 00:37:09,873
And I remember reaching over thinking,

586
00:37:09,893 --> 00:37:12,174
I thought I saw a table when I came into the room,

587
00:37:12,815 --> 00:37:13,796
not really believing it,

588
00:37:14,156 --> 00:37:16,398
and feeling an actual controller

589
00:37:16,778 --> 00:37:20,701
exactly where this virtual eye told me it would be.

590
00:37:21,122 --> 00:37:22,703
And feeling that in my hand

591
00:37:22,783 --> 00:37:25,886
was one of the most amazing moments I've had.

592
00:37:26,990 --> 00:37:30,112
when VR gets this right, it's amazing.

593
00:37:30,152 --> 00:37:31,732
And it wasn't very high resolution.

594
00:37:32,212 --> 00:37:33,833
It was really just a simple trick

595
00:37:34,213 --> 00:37:37,194
of combining that haptic feedback

596
00:37:37,214 --> 00:37:38,455
of what I could feel in my hand

597
00:37:38,515 --> 00:37:40,195
with what my visual system told me,

598
00:37:40,576 --> 00:37:42,917
and it was exactly where it was supposed to be.

599
00:37:43,317 --> 00:37:45,237
That's really a part of the critical thing,

600
00:37:45,257 --> 00:37:47,638
and part of what I think is the magic of VR,

601
00:37:48,039 --> 00:37:49,499
and what we're really aiming for here.

602
00:37:49,559 --> 00:37:50,840
So go for that feeling.

603
00:37:51,180 --> 00:37:53,842
I've had a lot of people say, yeah, VR isn't ready yet.

604
00:37:53,862 --> 00:37:55,163
You know, we need another 20 years.

605
00:37:55,723 --> 00:37:58,065
No, I think you have that kind of experience.

606
00:37:58,125 --> 00:38:00,727
And how many people here experiencing

607
00:38:00,787 --> 00:38:04,030
VR had at some point that amazing, whoa,

608
00:38:04,070 --> 00:38:06,031
this is way more real than I thought it would be?

609
00:38:06,071 --> 00:38:06,792
Can I see hands?

610
00:38:06,832 --> 00:38:07,012
Yeah.

611
00:38:07,292 --> 00:38:08,093
Look at how many hands.

